library("skimr")

From the authors of the data source: The aim of this study was to unravel the role of predation in key pests (A. aurantii) associated with perennial citrus crops by quantifying the importance of species-specific trophic links employing, among others, molecular techniques. Specifically, i) the contribution of predation as a biotic mortality factor of A. aurantiiwas weighted using exclusion techniques and ii) the relative importance of potential predators was assessed through detection of prey DNA in theirgut contents.

To understand how A. aurantii individuals predation affect the trees they prey on, lets take a look at the tree samples used in this study! What are their orientations and what parts of them were compared?

predation %>%
  select(TREE, `TREE WRIENTATIWN`, `PLANT PART`, TREATMENT) %>%
  filter(TREATMENT == "Predation") %>%
  arrange(`PLANT PART`)

What are the mortality and parasitism rates after A. aurantiis predation?

Lets see if there is a correlation between predation and tree mortality!

ggplot(data=predation, mapping=aes(x=TREATMENT, y=MORTALITY, group = TREATMENT, fill = TREATMENT)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Are trees that became parasited more prone to die?

predation %>%
  filter(PARASITISM > 1) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=0.01 * PARASITISM, x= 0.01 * MORTALITY, color = `PLANT PART`)) +
  geom_point()+
  scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Dark2")+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE)+
  labs(title = "Parasitism Rate vs. Mortality",
       y = "Parasitism rate",
       x = "Mortality")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 12))

Do A. aurantii smaple individuals have a favorite part of the tree to predate on?

predation %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=`PREDATED SCALES`, fill=`PLANT PART`))+
  geom_bar(position = position_fill(), stat = "count")+ 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+
  labs(title = "Observations by tree parts that were predated",
       x = "Parts of the tree", 
       y = "Percent that were predated",
       fill= "Parts")+
  coord_flip()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 12))

Leaf seems to be the preferred part to predate on for Aurantii individuals; lets now see if there is such a relationship between trees orientation too!

predation %>% 
  filter(`PREDATED SCALES` > 30 & `PREDATED SCALES` < 42) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`PREDATED SCALES`, fill=`GENERATION`))+
geom_bar(alpha=0.9, na.rm=T, position="dodge")+
  theme(legend.position = "right",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust=1))+
  labs(title = "Observations by generations of the predated trees",
       x = "Predation scales",
       fill= "Generation")+
theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 12))

We now know that there is a positive correlation between mortality and A. aurantii predation, does that have anything to do with the aurantii individuals preferred parts of the tree?

predation %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=`PREDATED SCALES`, y=MORTALITY, color=`PLANT PART`))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_point(shape = 18)+
  labs(title = "Observations of mortality in relation to predation, grouped by plant parts",
       x = "# Predation",
       fill= "Plant Parts")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 10))

Now, lets see if mortality rate has a different distribution between different parts of the sample trees!

predation %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = MORTALITY)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~`PLANT PART`)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

predation %>%
  filter(MORTALITY > 50) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = MORTALITY)) +
  geom_density(fill="steelblue", alpha=0.4)+
  facet_wrap(~`PLANT PART`)
